      "writtenOn": "2021-01-20T21:08:39Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": ":( \nHow hard would it be to restructure things to avoid the mutable? Can the initialValue go on the `Var` instead of the `Declare`?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 73,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 73,
        "endChar": 12
      },
      "revId": "7fd3c08e99d2a3c268e1517310dfd1ae4d5aa592",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c74367c7_7d59deb2",
        "filename": "src/sksl/ir/SkSLVariable.h",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 73,
      "author": {
        "id": 5640
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-01-20T22:20:14Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That would be ok for things like a \u003d 0, but I\u0027m not a fan of forcing the user to take something like Declare(a, Sqrt(b)) and move the calculation up out of the natural flow. It would make the code harder to both read and write, and I\u0027d rather have a tiny bit of ugliness in our code than make all user-written DSL code worse forevermore.\n\nI of course initially thought \"oh, I\u0027ll just make the Variable* non-const so I can modify it\", but that immediately turned into a nightmare - among other things, SymbolTable::takeOwnershipOfSymbol makes things const (for good reason).\n\nI\u0027m certainly no fan of mutable, but I didn\u0027t think this case was egregious. The Variable doesn\u0027t actually own the value - it belongs to the VarDeclaration, and this is just a pointer that gives us convenient access to it. I conceptually don\u0027t feel like changing this value is changing the Variable object at all, so it seemed like a textbook case in which mutable made sense.\n\nThere are of course ways to fix this, like tracking the initial values in some context structure external to the Variable or restructuring the calls to IRGenerator so that the DSL handles the creation of the Variable (which would be fairly unnatural), but everything I thought of seemed uglier to me than just making this mutable. Thoughts?",
      "parentUuid": "1ac52a1d_03d7cf26",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 73,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 73,
        "endChar": 12
      },
      "revId": "7fd3c08e99d2a3c268e1517310dfd1ae4d5aa592",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "8c8695a6_6dc89c3b",
        "filename": "src/sksl/ir/SkSLVariable.h",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 73,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-01-20T22:44:19Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Is it hard to make the Variable have a pointer to its VarDeclaration instead, and then setInitialValue could set the varDecl\u0027s value const-safely?\n\nI\u0027d like Brian\u0027s opinion re mutable if there\u0027s no clean way to remove it. I know at one point a lot of his fixes for built-ins hinged on fixing const-correctness and getting rid of mutable, and I would hate to regress on that front.",
      "parentUuid": "c74367c7_7d59deb2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 73,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 73,
        "endChar": 12
      },
      "revId": "7fd3c08e99d2a3c268e1517310dfd1ae4d5aa592",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "2e5a8fc9_914bbc7a",
        "filename": "src/sksl/ir/SkSLVariable.h",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 73,
      "author": {
        "id": 5631
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-01-21T14:21:04Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Rambling train-of-thought...\n\nI looked at this last night, and wanted to noodle on it. I assume that having a pointer to the VarDeclaration poses the same problem - the Variable exists before the Declaration, so *that* pointer would need to be mutable?\n\nI know I previously asked about having the Declare be the thing that actually creates the Variable, too - but I remember that didn\u0027t make much sense (and because the Variable needs to be a C++ thing, it does seem like a problem).\n\nThe mutable does give me pause, though - when I got rid of all those, it was part of guaranteeing that we couldn\u0027t (accidentally) be modifying shared data owned by the pre-includes. That doesn\u0027t seem like an issue right now, but I don\u0027t want to stumble back into that corner later.\n\nRe-educate me: In the context of the DSL, can a single thing both create the Var object, and emit the declaration? Today (before this CL), you can use Var() to create dangling references to variables that are never declared. That functionality is useful for things that are known to be declared elsewhere (builtins), but the common case is that *every* Var is going to have to be accompanied by a Declare, right? Given that, can the common constructor for Var also serve as the Declare somehow? I guess this is awkward/impossible, as all statement factories (including Declare) need to return their statement...\n\nAlternately, it could look like:\n\n  Var foo(type, name, initialValue);\n  ...\n  foo.declare();\n\nWhich isn\u0027t much different from John\u0027s first idea, and still has the same basic issue. (Plus it makes the declaration look very different from other statements.\n\n... so, I\u0027m willing to concede - I think the DSL code will read much more naturally as written here, and I also think the mutable isn\u0027t a huge risk - we\u0027re still only modifying variables that were created nearby -- (hopefully) - can we add some error checks to prevent someone from writing:\n\n  Declare(Var(kFloat4, \"sk_FragColor\"), \"...\")",
      "parentUuid": "8c8695a6_6dc89c3b",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 73,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 73,
        "endChar": 12
      },
      "revId": "7fd3c08e99d2a3c268e1517310dfd1ae4d5aa592",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d0f53289_055cd57d",
        "filename": "src/sksl/ir/SkSLVariable.h",
